clips:
  - id: ac6c1142-312b-4772-a316-f7debe5e9c48
    start: 00:10.3
    end: 00:27.72
    fields:
      transcription: |
        日本の神話には、ギリシャ神話のように、人間的な神様がたくさん出てきて活躍する面白い話が多く残っている。その中に天照大神という神様についての有名な話がある。どんな話か読んでみよう。
      meaning: In Japanese mythology, just as in Greek mythology, many interesting stories remain in which many humanlike gods appear and play active roles. Among these, there is a famous story about the goddess called Amaterasu-Ōmikami. Let’s read and see what kind of story it is.
    tags:
      &a1
      - tobira06
  - id: 14454624-2ac9-4263-8683-98f954fee6f3
    start: 00:29.48
    end: 00:44.1
    fields:
      transcription: 昔々、大昔、日本には天照大神という、神様の中でもっとも偉い太陽の神様がいて、高天原という昔の日本を治めていました。
      meaning: Long ago, in ancient times in Japan there was a sun goddess called Amaterasu-Ōmikami, who was the highest ranking of all the gods and who ruled over ancient Japan, which was called Takamagahara.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 48268204-a7b4-48c7-9a2c-fdf37f31fe42
    start: 00:45.488
    end: 00:59.248
    fields:
      transcription: 天照大神には須佐之男命という弟の神様がいたのですが、須佐之男はとても乱暴で悪いことばかりするので、人々はとても困っていました。
      meaning: Amaterasu-Ōmikami had a younger brother god named Susano 'o-no-mikoto, but because Susano’o was very violent and did nothing but bad things, the people were very troubled.
    tags:
      - tobira06
  - id: 2075df98-2fb0-4799-a413-26fdf5e9e6d8
    start: 01:00.548
    end: 01:19.704
    fields:
      transcription: ある日、須佐之男は天照の侍女を間違って殺してしまいました。それを知った天照は弟の乱暴に怒って岩の中に隠れてしまい、昼だった世界は急に夜のように暗くなってしまいました。
      meaning: One day, Susano’o killed Amaterasu’s lady attendant by mistake. Amaterasu, after finding out about this, became angry at her brother’s violence and hid herself away inside a rock (cave) so that the world, which had been in daylight, suddenly became as dark as night.
    tags:
      - tobira06
  - id: 54c47dc8-0314-4bb4-b51e-5a0f1e30e312
    start: 01:21.4
    end: 01:31.18
    fields:
      transcription: 太陽の神様の天照が岩の中に隠れて外に出て来ないため、世界は何日も真っ暗な日が続きました。
      meaning: Because Amaterasu, the sun goddess, hid inside the rock (cave) and did not come out, several days of complete darkness continued in the world.
    tags: *a1
  - id: b5359410-3560-4400-951f-8e1f416edc86
    start: 01:33.064
    end: 01:48.724
    fields:
      transcription: 困ってしまった他の神様達は、天照に岩の外に出て来てもらおうと、彼女が隠れている岩戸の前でお酒を飲みながら歌ったり踊ったり笑ったりして、大騒ぎをしました。
      meaning: The other gods, who were at a loss, tried to get Amaterasu to come out by drinking, singing, dancing, and making a great noise in front of the rock door where she was hiding.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 461c6b05-a603-481d-8866-46d7daf03340
    start: 01:49.88
    end: 01:57.26
    fields:
      transcription: そうすれば、天照はみんなが何をしているんだろうと思って外に出て来ると考えたわけです。
      meaning: They thought that by doing so Amaterasu would wonder what everyone was doing and come outside.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 35e6cfb5-6050-4d1f-b580-9bdfa9489707
    start: 01:58.34
    end: 02:04.8
    fields:
      transcription: 神様達は真っ暗な中で、一生懸命歌ったり踊ったり、笑ったりしました。
      meaning: The gods sang, danced, and laughed with utmost effort in complete darkness.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 5afaa74e-3263-4045-b26b-dae64857d99d
    start: 02:06.12
    end: 02:21.08
    fields:
      transcription: 外の大騒ぎを不思議に思った天照が少しだけ岩戸を開けてみると、その瞬間を待っていた力持ちの神様が岩戸を全部開けて、天照を岩の外に出してしまいました。
      meaning: Thinking the great noise outside was strange, Amaterasu opened the rock door only a little bit; then, a mighty god, who had been waiting for that moment, opened the rock door all the way and pulled Amaterasu out of the rock.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 731e6f23-896d-4a9f-b773-06b7ea42ffb0
    start: 02:22.56
    end: 02:29.18
    fields:
      transcription: |
        天照が外に出て来たので、世界は明るくなって、また昼が戻ってきたそうです。
      meaning: Because Amaterasu came outside, the world was said to have become bright, and daylight returned once again.
    tags: *a1
  - id: e456010d-1883-421e-9359-8c5e623958fa
    start: 02:30.44
    end: 02:43.42
    fields:
      transcription: この話は、昔の人が日食を説明するために作った神話ではないかと言われている。何も知らなかった昔の人々にとって、日食はとても怖いことだったのだろう。
      meaning: It is said that this story was probably a myth that ancient people created to explain a solar eclipse. To ancient people who did not know anything about them, solar eclipses must have been very frightening things.
    tags: *a1
  - id: 20cb8601-6838-468f-a374-f7564a27a934
    start: 02:44.076
    end: 02:56.996
    fields:
      transcription: また、この神話からも分かるように、昔から神様は日本人にとって、人間と同じように笑ったり怒ったり喧嘩したりする親しみやすい存在だったのだ。
      meaning: In addition, as we understand from this myth, since early times the gods, who did things like laugh, get angry, and fight like human beings, were approachable to Japanese people.
    tags: *a1
  - id: b6962cad-d0ea-41cf-b0bd-6d5b1f0c38ce
    start: 02:57.78
    end: 03:15.94
    fields:
      transcription: この天照大神を祭る神社は、日本全国に一万八千ぐらいあると言われていて、毎年多くの人々がお参りに訪れる。天照大神は二十一世紀の現在でも大忙し！ということだ。
      meaning: There are said to be around 18,000 shrines throughout Japan dedicated to Amaterasu-Ōmikami, and every year many people go to visit them. This means that even today in the 21st century Amaterasu-Ōmikami is very busy!
    tags: *a1
